# 📦 SUMMARY  
# This set of commands stops an existing Jenkins container, runs a new Jenkins container with Docker socket mounted,  
# installs Docker CLI inside Jenkins, adjusts socket permissions, and verifies Docker inside Jenkins by pulling an image.  
# Language/Platform: Bash (Linux/macOS shell, Docker CLI)  
# What you'll learn: Running Jenkins with Docker-in-Docker capabilities, configuring permissions, and testing Docker inside container.  
# Outcome: Jenkins can control Docker on the host, enabling building and running containers from Jenkins jobs.  
# Why this matters: Essential for Jenkins pipelines that build, test, or deploy Docker containers using the host Docker engine.  

ssh root@<dropletip>  
# ✅ What it does: Connects to the remote server as root via SSH.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Needed to manage Docker containers and Jenkins on the remote host.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Stop Existing Jenkins Container  
# ------------------------------  
docker ps  
# ✅ What it does: Lists all running Docker containers with IDs and names.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Helps you identify which Jenkins container to stop.  

docker stop <jenkins_container_id>  
# ✅ What it does: Stops the running Jenkins container gracefully.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Prevents conflicts when starting a new Jenkins container with updated configuration.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: (Optional) List Docker Volumes  
# ------------------------------  
docker volume ls  
# ✅ What it does: Lists all Docker volumes on the host.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Confirms that `jenkins_home` exists or helps clean unused volumes if needed.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Run Jenkins Container with Docker Socket Mounted  
# ------------------------------  
docker run -p 8080:8080 -p 50000:50000 -d \
-v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \
-v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \
jenkins/jenkins:lts
  
# ✅ What it does: Starts Jenkins container in detached mode, mapping ports and mounting volumes.  
# 🧠 Why it matters:  
#    - Jenkins can access the host Docker daemon through the mounted socket.  
#    - Allows Jenkins jobs to run Docker commands (build, run, push images) without running Docker-in-Docker.  
# 🧠 How it works (broken down):  
#    - `-p 8080:8080` → maps Jenkins web UI inside container to port 8080 on host for browser access.  
#    - `-p 50000:50000` → maps Jenkins agent port for distributed builds.  
#    - `-v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home` → persists Jenkins configurations, jobs, and plugins across container restarts.  
#    - `-v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock` → mounts host Docker socket inside container, allowing Jenkins to control host Docker.  
#    - `-d` → runs container in the background so the terminal is free.  

# ✅ Outcome:  
# Jenkins can now execute Docker commands as if Docker were installed inside the container itself.  
# Example commands you can run from Jenkins jobs:  
#    - `docker ps` → list running containers on the host.  
#    - `docker build -t myapp:1.0 .` → build images from Jenkins workspace.  
#    - `docker run -d myapp:1.0` → start containers directly from Jenkins pipeline.  

# 🧠 Why it matters in CI/CD:  
# This setup allows full automation of containerized workflows, including building, testing, and deploying Docker images directly from Jenkins pipelines without installing Docker inside the container itself.  

docker ps  
# ✅ What it does: Verifies the Jenkins container is running with the new settings.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Access Jenkins Container Shell as Root  
# ------------------------------  
docker exec -u 0 -it <jenkins_container_id> bash  
# ✅ What it does: Opens an interactive root shell inside Jenkins container.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Required to install Docker CLI and adjust socket permissions.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `docker exec` → run a command inside a container.  
#    - `-u 0` → run as root user.  
#    - `-it` → interactive terminal session.  
#    - `bash` → launches shell.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Install Docker CLI Inside Jenkins Container  
# ------------------------------  
curl https://get.docker.com/ -o dockerinstall && chmod +x dockerinstall && ./dockerinstall  
# ✅ What it does:  
# Downloads the official Docker installation script, makes it executable, and runs it to install Docker CLI inside the Jenkins container.  

# 🧠 Why it matters:  
# 1. The Jenkins container needs the Docker CLI (command-line interface) to run commands like `docker build`, `docker run`, and `docker push`.  
# 2. Even though Docker itself runs on the host, without the CLI inside the container, Jenkins cannot talk to the host Docker daemon through the mounted socket.  
# 3. This allows full CI/CD workflows using Docker directly from Jenkins pipelines.  

# 🧠 How it works (broken down step-by-step):  
# 1. `curl https://get.docker.com/ -o dockerinstall`  
#    - Downloads the official Docker install script from Docker’s website.  
#    - `-o dockerinstall` → saves the script locally with the name `dockerinstall`.  
#    - Why: We need a script file to run; downloading it ensures we get the latest Docker installer.  
# 2. `chmod +x dockerinstall`  
#    - Makes the downloaded script executable (`+x`).  
#    - Why: Linux/Unix requires scripts to have execute permission before they can be run.  
# 3. `./dockerinstall`  
#    - Runs the installation script.  
#    - Why: The script automatically installs the Docker CLI inside the container, including required binaries and configuration.  
#    - How: It detects the container OS, downloads the appropriate Docker binaries, and sets them up so the `docker` command is available in the container.  

# 🧠 Additional Notes:  
# - This does **not** install the Docker daemon inside the container; it uses the host Docker daemon via the mounted `/var/run/docker.sock`.  
# - Make sure to run this as root or with permissions that allow installing software inside the container.  
# - After this, you can run commands like `docker ps`, `docker images`, `docker build` directly from Jenkins.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Check and Update Docker Socket Permissions  
# ------------------------------  
ls -l /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Lists the Docker socket file with detailed permissions, owner, and group.  
# 🧠 Why it matters:  
#    - Shows whether the Jenkins user inside the container can read/write to the host Docker daemon.  
#    - Default permissions often restrict access to the root user or Docker group, which can cause "permission denied" errors.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `ls -l` → long listing format, shows:  
#        - File type (`s` for socket)  
#        - Permissions (read/write/execute for user, group, others)  
#        - Owner and group  
#    - You can verify if the container’s Jenkins user can access `/var/run/docker.sock`.  

chmod 666 /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Changes permissions so all users can read/write the Docker socket.  
# 🧠 Why it matters:  
#    - Ensures Jenkins jobs can run Docker commands without "permission denied" errors.  
#    - Allows non-root users inside the container to communicate with host Docker daemon.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `chmod 666` → sets read/write permissions for:  
#        - User (owner)  
#        - Group  
#        - Others  
#    - 6 = read (4) + write (2), applied to each category.  
#    - After this, any user in the container can execute Docker commands via the mounted socket.  

ls -l /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Lists the socket again to confirm the updated permissions.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Verifies that permission changes took effect and Jenkins can now safely use Docker commands.  

exit  
# ✅ What it does: Exits the interactive container shell and returns to the host shell.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Finishes the configuration process inside the container, returning you to host control.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `exit` closes the bash session inside the Jenkins container.  
#    - You can continue running commands on the host, or start Jenkins jobs that now have Docker access.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Access Jenkins Again for Testing  
# ------------------------------  
docker exec -it <jenkins_container_id> bash  
# ✅ What it does: Opens an interactive shell session inside the running Jenkins container.  
# 🧠 Why it matters:  
#    - Lets you manually test Docker commands from within the Jenkins container.  
#    - Useful to verify Docker CLI and mounted socket configuration before running actual jobs.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `docker exec` → execute a command inside a running container.  
#    - `-it` → allocates a pseudo-TTY and keeps it interactive, so you can type commands.  
#    - `<jenkins_container_id>` → replace with actual container ID from `docker ps`.  
#    - `bash` → starts a Bash shell inside the container.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Test Docker Inside Jenkins Container  
# ------------------------------  
docker pull redis  
# ✅ What it does: Pulls the official Redis image from Docker Hub to the host via Jenkins container.  
# 🧠 Why it matters:  
#    - Confirms the Jenkins container can communicate with the host Docker daemon through the mounted socket.  
#    - Validates that Docker CLI inside the container works as expected.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    - `docker pull <image>` → fetches the specified image and all its layers from Docker Hub.  
#    - The image is stored on the host, not inside the container itself, because Docker commands run on the host.  
#    - If this command succeeds, Jenkins can now build, run, and push Docker images from pipelines.  
# 🧠 Extra verification tip:  
#    - Run `docker images` after the pull to confirm the Redis image exists on the host.  
#    - Run `docker run -d -p 6379:6379 redis` to start a container as a final functional test.  

# ------------------------------  
# ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
# ------------------------------  
# - Replace <jenkins_container_id> with actual ID from `docker ps`.  
# - Mounting Docker socket gives Jenkins full access to host Docker; only do this in trusted environments.  
# - For safer permissions, add Jenkins user to Docker group instead of chmod 666.  
# - Test Docker CLI version: `docker --version`.  
# - Restart Jenkins container if Docker commands fail unexpectedly.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Windows PowerShell Equivalent  
# ------------------------------  
winpty docker exec -u 0 -it <jenkins_container_id> bash  
# ✅ What it does: Opens an interactive root shell inside Jenkins container on Windows.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: PowerShell cannot handle interactive shells natively; `winpty` fixes this.  
# 🧠 How it works:  
#    1. `winpty` → wraps terminal commands so PowerShell can handle input/output correctly.  
#    2. `docker exec` → runs a command inside the container.  
#    3. `-u 0` → executes as root.  
#    4. `-it` → interactive terminal.  
#    5. `bash` → starts Bash shell in container.  
# 🔥 Tip: Replace `<jenkins_container_id>` with actual container ID or name from `docker ps`.  
